Disclaimer: The data for this R Notebook have been purposefully altered for the purposes of display in my portfolio. The original data are sensitive, as the study is ongoing and has not been published yet.

The purpose of this R Notebook is to investigate differences in mouse growth (weight, length, and BMI) across age (day 1 to day 9) between different genotypes (WT - wildtype (control), Het - heterozygous, KO - knock-out (mutant)), sexes (M, F), and litter sizes (1 - 6 mice).

Definitions:

  • Genotype - genetic makeup of the mouse, in this case, with reference to a single gene
  • WT - wildtype - mouse has two normal copies of the gene
  • Het - heterozygous - mouse has one normal copy and one mutated copy of the gene
  • KO - knock-out - mouse has two mutated copies of the gene

1. Raw Data Import and Transformation/Normalization

First, the raw weight and raw length data is imported, and all of the calculations and transformations are done internally within R to avoid error propagation that is prone to occur in Excel with copying and pasting.

#Load all needed libraries
suppressMessages(library(tidyr))
suppressMessages(library(reshape2))
suppressMessages(library(ggplot2))
suppressMessages(library(grid))
suppressMessages(library(ggsignif))
suppressMessages(library(ggpubr))
suppressMessages(library(dplyr))
suppressMessages(library(plyr))
#Read the csv data file into R
#PC:
RawWeight = read.csv("C:/Users/Julie/Dropbox/Julie's Stuff/Portfolio/Growth/Growth/RawWeight.csv", header = TRUE)
RawLength = read.csv("C:/Users/Julie/Dropbox/Julie's Stuff/Portfolio/Growth/Growth/RawLength.csv", header = TRUE)
#Tidy the RawWeight
RawWeight$Sex[which(RawWeight$Sex == "f")] <- "F"
RawWeight$Sex[which(RawWeight$Sex == "m")] <- "M"
RawWeight$Sex <- factor(RawWeight$Sex, levels = c("F","M"))
RawWeight <- RawWeight[complete.cases(RawWeight$X6),]
names(RawWeight)[1] <- "PupID"
names(RawWeight)[6] <- "1"
names(RawWeight)[7] <- "2"
names(RawWeight)[8] <- "3"
names(RawWeight)[9] <- "4"
names(RawWeight)[10] <- "5"
names(RawWeight)[11] <- "6"
names(RawWeight)[12] <- "7"
names(RawWeight)[13] <- "8"
names(RawWeight)[14] <- "9"
#Tidy the RawLength
RawLength$Sex[which(RawLength$Sex == "f")] <- "F"
RawLength$Sex[which(RawLength$Sex == "m")] <- "M"
RawLength$Sex <- factor(RawLength$Sex, levels = c("F","M"))
RawLength <- RawLength[complete.cases(RawLength$X6),]
names(RawLength)[1] <- "PupID"
names(RawLength)[6] <- "1"
names(RawLength)[7] <- "2"
names(RawLength)[8] <- "3"
names(RawLength)[9] <- "4"
names(RawLength)[10] <- "5"
names(RawLength)[11] <- "6"
names(RawLength)[12] <- "7"
names(RawLength)[13] <- "8"
names(RawLength)[14] <- "9"
#Creating Weight Gain variable
RawWeight$WTGain <- RawWeight$`9`-RawWeight$`1`
RawWeight <- RawWeight[complete.cases(RawWeight$`9`),]
#Creating Length Gain variable
RawLength$LNGain <- RawLength$`9`-RawLength$`1`
RawLength <- RawLength[complete.cases(RawLength$`9`),]
#Transforming wide data to long format and merging datasets
WeightData <- melt(RawWeight, variable.name = "Age", value.name = "Weight", 
                   id.vars = c("PupID","Litter", "LitterSize","Geno", "Sex", "WTGain"))
LengthData <- melt(RawLength, variable.name = "Age", value.name = "Length", 
                   id.vars = c("PupID","Litter", "LitterSize","Geno", "Sex", "LNGain"))
Data <- merge(WeightData, LengthData, by=c("PupID", "Litter", "Sex", "LitterSize", "Geno", "Age"))
#Creating BMI variable
Data$BMI <- (Data$Weight/((Data$Length*Data$Length)))*1000
#Change all factors into factor data types
Data$PupID <- as.factor(Data$PupID)
Data$LitterSize <- as.factor(Data$LitterSize)
Data$Geno <- as.factor(Data$Geno)
Data$Sex <- as.factor(Data$Sex)
Data$AgeFactor <- as.factor(Data$Age)
Data$Geno <- factor(Data$Geno, levels =c("WT", "Het", "KO"))
#Make data subsets
DataLS2to5 <- Data[which(Data$LitterSize =="2" | Data$LitterSize=="3"| 
                           Data$LitterSize=="4"| Data$LitterSize=="5"),]
DataP1 <- Data[which(Data$Age == "1"),]
DataP9 <- Data[which(Data$Age == "9"),]

2. Data Visualization and Analysis

#Create function to apply the same style to each chart
addtheme <- function(chart, title, subtitle, legend_pos){
  chart +
    labs(title = title, subtitle = subtitle)+
    theme_minimal()+
    theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
          panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
          panel.border = element_blank(),
          panel.background = element_blank(),
          plot.title = element_text(size = 12, face = "bold"),
          axis.title = element_text(face="bold"),
          axis.text.x = element_text(colour="black", size = 10),
          axis.text.y = element_text(colour="black", size = 10),
          axis.line.x = element_line(size = 0.5, colour = "black"),
          axis.line.y = element_line(size = 0.5, colour = "black"),
          legend.position = legend_pos)
}
#Create a function for generating box plots with my preferred parameters
bp <- function(data, x, y, fill, xaxis, yaxis, ylim, title, subtitle, 
               color_name, colors, legend_lab, legend_pos)
{
  chart <- ggplot(data, aes(x=x, y=y, fill = fill))+
    geom_boxplot(alpha=0.7)+
    scale_x_discrete(name=xaxis)+
    scale_y_continuous(name=yaxis, limits = ylim)+
    scale_fill_manual(color_name, values=colors, labels = legend_lab) +
    stat_compare_means(label="p.signif", method="anova", hide.ns=TRUE, 
                       label.y = ylim[2], size = signif_size)
  
  chart <- addtheme(chart,title, subtitle, legend_pos)
}
#Create a function for generating box plots using brewer pallete with my preferred parameters
brewer_bp <- function(data, x, y, fill, xaxis, yaxis, ylim, title, subtitle, 
                      color_name, palette = "RdBu", legend_lab, legend_pos){
  chart <- ggplot(data, aes(x=x, y=y, fill = fill))+
    geom_boxplot(alpha=0.7)+
    scale_x_discrete(name=xaxis)+
    scale_y_continuous(name=yaxis, limits = ylim)+
    scale_fill_brewer(color_name, palette = "RdBu", labels = legend_lab)+
    stat_compare_means(label="p.signif", method="anova", hide.ns=TRUE, 
                       label.y = ylim[2], size = signif_size)
  
  chart <- addtheme(chart,title, subtitle, legend_pos)
}
#Create a function for generating density plots
densityplot <- function(data, x, color_group, xaxis, title, subtitle, 
                        color_name, colors, legend_lab, legend_pos){
  chart <- ggplot(data, aes(x=x, color = color_group))+
    geom_density(size=1.5)+
    scale_x_continuous(name= xaxis)+
    scale_y_continuous(name="Density")+
    scale_color_manual(color_name, values = colors, labels = legend_lab)
  
  chart <- addtheme(chart,title, subtitle, legend_pos)
}
#Create a function for generating line plots
lp <- function(data, x, y, xaxis, yaxis, ylim, color, title, subtitle, 
               color_name, colors, line_col = "darkred", legend_lab, legend_pos){
  chart <- ggplot(data, aes(x=x, y=y, color = color)) + 
    geom_point(size = 3) + 
    geom_smooth(method=lm, linetype="dashed", color=line_col, fill="#E8F5FF") +
    scale_x_continuous(name=xaxis)+
    scale_y_continuous(name=yaxis, limits = ylim)+
    scale_color_manual(color_name, values=colors, labels = legend_lab)
  
  chart <- addtheme(chart,title, subtitle, legend_pos)
}
#Generating custom legends with sample sizes
geno_lab <- c(paste("WT (",count(Data$Geno[which(Data$Geno == "WT" & Data$Age == "9")])[2],")"),
              paste("Het (",count(Data$Geno[which(Data$Geno == "Het" & Data$Age == "9")])[2],")"),
              paste("KO (",count(Data$Geno[which(Data$Geno == "KO" & Data$Age == "9")])[2],")"))
sex_lab <- c(paste("F (",count(Data$Sex[which(Data$Sex == "F" & Data$Age == "9")])[2],")"),
             paste("M (",count(Data$Sex[which(Data$Sex == "M" & Data$Age == "9")])[2],")"))
LS_lab <- c(paste("1 (",count(Data$LitterSize[which(Data$LitterSize == "1" 
                                                    & Data$Age == "9")])[2],")"),
            paste("2 (",count(Data$LitterSize[which(Data$LitterSize == "2" 
                                                    & Data$Age == "9")])[2],")"),
            paste("3 (",count(Data$LitterSize[which(Data$LitterSize == "3" 
                                                    & Data$Age == "9")])[2],")"),
            paste("4 (",count(Data$LitterSize[which(Data$LitterSize == "4" 
                                                    & Data$Age == "9")])[2],")"),
            paste("5 (",count(Data$LitterSize[which(Data$LitterSize == "5" 
                                                    & Data$Age == "9")])[2],")"),
            paste("6 (",count(Data$LitterSize[which(Data$LitterSize == "6" 
                                                     & Data$Age == "9")])[2],")"))
#Common plot parameters:
#Colors for genotypes
geno_colors <- c('#BBBBBB','#78D2FF','#001987')
#Colors for sexes
sex_colors <- c('#BBBBBB','#000000')
#Color of lines
lines <- "#1F3552"
#Size of significance markers
signif_size <- 5
#Custom legend positions
bottom_right <- c(0.8,0.2)
top_right <- c(0.9,0.8)

2.1 Raw Data

Mice were housed under normal conditions (12hr light/12 hr dark; food ad libidum), and were weighed (g) and length was measured (mm) at nine different time points (ages 1 - 9). Weight gain and length gain were calculated as the difference between measures at age 1 and 9. BMI was calculated as: (weight (g)/ length2 (mm2)) x 1000.

2.1.1 Raw Weight Across Age

#Boxplot Parameters for Raw Weight
xaxis <- "Age (arbitrary units)"
yaxis <- "Weight (g)"
subtitle <- "Litters of all sizes"
ylim <- c(round(min(Data$Weight)-1),round(max(Data$Weight)+1))
#Boxplot of raw weight across age, divided by genotype
title <- "Raw Weight by Genotype"
plotA <- bp(Data, x=Data$AgeFactor, y=Data$Weight, fill=Data$Geno, 
                   xaxis, yaxis, ylim, title, subtitle, color_name = "Genotype", 
                   colors = geno_colors, legend_lab = geno_lab, legend_pos = bottom_right)
#Boxplot of raw weight across age, divided by sex
title <- "Raw Weight by Sex"
plotB <- bp(Data, x=Data$AgeFactor, y=Data$Weight, fill=Data$Sex, 
                   xaxis, yaxis="", ylim, title, subtitle, color_name = "Sex", 
                   colors = sex_colors, legend_lab = sex_lab, legend_pos = bottom_right)
#Boxplot of raw weight across age, divided by litter size
title <- "Raw Weight by Litter Size"
plotC <- brewer_bp(Data, x=Data$AgeFactor, y=Data$Weight, fill=Data$LitterSize, 
                   xaxis, yaxis, ylim, title, subtitle, color_name = "Litter Size", 
                   legend_lab = LS_lab, legend_pos = "right")
#Arrange boxplots into 3 panels
suppressWarnings(ggarrange(plotA, plotB, labels = c("A.","B."), ncol = 2, nrow = 1))

suppressWarnings(ggarrange(plotC, labels = c("C."), ncol = 1, nrow = 1))

Observations

Genotype
When all litter sizes and both sexes are included, there is no significant effect of genotype on raw weight across age. However, there is a trend of control (WT, grey) mice weighing less than mutant (KO, dark blue) mice.

Sex
There is a strong effect of mouse sex on growth. On average, males are larger than females.

Litter Size
There is a strong effect of litter size on mouse weight. Mice from larger litters (blue) have lower starting weights and grow less across the ages tested as compared to mice from small litters (red).

suppressWarnings(ggarrange(plotE, plotF, labels = c("E.","F."), ncol = 2, nrow = 1))

Observations
As expected from previous charts, there is a strong effect of litter size on weight gain and length gain. There appears to be a trend of decreasing BMI with increasing litter size, however, this was not found to be significant. This may be due to the fact that weight and length decrease proportionally with litter size, thereby resulting in relatively constant BMI. This also appears to be the case for different genotypes and sexes.

2.1.5. Effect of litter size on weight gain and length gain

In addition to an effect of litter size, the boxplots suggest that there may be an effect of genotype, as well as an effect of sex. The weight and length data are approximately normally distributed (see density plots below), and a linear model is fit to the data.

#Density Plots for Weight Gain
xaxis <- "Weight Gain (g)"
title <- "Weight Gain by Genotype"
plotA <- densityplot(DataP9, DataP9$WTGain, color_group = DataP9$Geno, xaxis, title, subtitle, color_name = "Geno", colors = geno_colors, legend_lab = geno_lab, legend_pos = top_right)
title <- "Weight Gain by Sex"
plotB <- densityplot(DataP9, DataP9$WTGain, color_group = DataP9$Sex, xaxis, title, subtitle, color_name = "Sex", colors = sex_colors, legend_lab = sex_lab, legend_pos = top_right)
#Density Plot for Length Gain
xaxis <- "Length Gain (mm)"
title <- "Length Gain by Genotype"
plotC <- densityplot(DataP9, DataP9$LNGain, color_group = DataP9$Geno, xaxis, title, subtitle, color_name = "Geno", colors = geno_colors, legend_lab = geno_lab, legend_pos = top_right)
title <- "Length Gain by Sex"
plotD <- densityplot(DataP9, DataP9$LNGain, color_group = DataP9$Sex, xaxis, title, subtitle, color_name = "Sex", colors = sex_colors, legend_lab = sex_lab, legend_pos = top_right)
suppressWarnings(ggarrange(plotA, plotB, labels = c("A.","B."), ncol = 2, nrow = 1))

suppressWarnings(ggarrange(plotC, plotD, labels = c("C.","D."), ncol = 2, nrow = 1))

#5. Build Linear Model and Check Significance
DataP9$LS_num <- as.numeric(DataP9$LitterSize)
model <- lm(DataP9$WTGain ~ DataP9$LS_num, data=DataP9)
modelSummary <- summary(model)
modelCoeffsWG <- modelSummary$coefficients
beta.estimate <- modelCoeffsWG["DataP9$LS_num", "Estimate"]
std.error <- modelCoeffsWG["DataP9$LS_num", "Std. Error"]
t_value <- beta.estimate/std.error
WGp_value <- format(round(2*pt(-abs(t_value), df=nrow(Data)-2),4), nsmall = 4)

Weight Gain

The formula y = -0.46x + 7.71 describes the relationship between mouse weight gain (y) and litter size (x). For every extra mouse in a litter, the mouse weight gain from age 1 toa ge 9 is reduced by 0.46g (p = 0.0000).

#5. Build Linear Model and Check Significance
model <- lm(DataP9$LNGain ~ DataP9$LS_num, data=DataP9)
modelSummary <- summary(model)
modelCoeffsLN <- modelSummary$coefficients
beta.estimate <- modelCoeffsLN["DataP9$LS_num", "Estimate"]
std.error <- modelCoeffsLN["DataP9$LS_num", "Std. Error"]
t_value <- beta.estimate/std.error
LNp_value <- format(round(2*pt(-abs(t_value), df=nrow(Data)-2),4), nsmall = 4)

Length Gain

The formula y = -0.77x + 28.62 describes the relationship between mouse length gain (y) and litter size (x). For every extra mouse in a litter, the mouse length gain from age 1 to age 9 is reduced by 0.77mm (p = 0.0000).

#Scatter and line plot for Weight Gain

                  "x + ",round(modelCoeffsWG[1],2))

suppressWarnings(ggarrange(plotA, plotB, labels = c("A.","B."),ncol = 2, nrow = 1))

2.1.6 Discussion

In order to account for the effect of litter size, data are normalized within each litter to the average heterozygous measures at age 9 (section 2.2), or at each age (section 2.3). In addition, analyses have been carried out on data from select litter sizes (litter sizes 2-5, section 2.5).

2.2 Data Normalized to Average Measures at Age 9 Heterozygous Mice (combined sexes) Within Litter

#Normalization to average age 9 Het within litter:
#Creating a normalized data set, wherein all data has been normalized to the average Het weight at age 9 within litter
#Normalized Weight
for(i in 1:length(levels(Data$Litter))){
  Data[which(Data$Litter == levels(Data$Litter)[i]),"NormWT"]<- Data[which(Data$Litter == levels(Data$Litter)[i]),"Weight"]/mean(Data[which(Data$Geno == "Het" & Data$Age == "9" & Data$Litter == levels(Data$Litter)[i]),"Weight"])
}
#Normalized Weight Gain
for(i in 1:length(levels(Data$Litter))){
  Data[which(Data$Litter == levels(Data$Litter)[i]),"NormWTGain"]<- Data[which(Data$Litter == levels(Data$Litter)[i]),"WTGain"]/mean(Data[which(Data$Geno == "Het" & Data$Age == "9" & Data$Litter == levels(Data$Litter)[i]),"WTGain"])
}
#Normalized Length
for(i in 1:length(levels(Data$Litter))){
  Data[which(Data$Litter == levels(Data$Litter)[i]),"NormLN"]<- Data[which(Data$Litter == levels(Data$Litter)[i]),"Length"]/mean(Data[which(Data$Geno == "Het" & Data$Age == "9" & Data$Litter == levels(Data$Litter)[i]),"Length"])
}
#Normalized Length Gain
for(i in 1:length(levels(Data$Litter))){
  Data[which(Data$Litter == levels(Data$Litter)[i]),"NormLNGain"]<- Data[which(Data$Litter == levels(Data$Litter)[i]),"LNGain"]/mean(Data[which(Data$Geno == "Het" & Data$Age == "9" & Data$Litter == levels(Data$Litter)[i]),"LNGain"])
}
#Normalized BMI
for(i in 1:length(levels(Data$Litter))){
  Data[which(Data$Litter == levels(Data$Litter)[i]),"NormBMI"]<- Data[which(Data$Litter == levels(Data$Litter)[i]),"BMI"]/mean(Data[which(Data$Geno == "Het" & Data$Age == "9" & Data$Litter == levels(Data$Litter)[i]),"BMI"])
}
#Creating subsets by sex
DataF <- Data[which(Data$Sex == "F"),]
DataM <- Data[which(Data$Sex == "M"),]
#Creating subsets by genotype
DataWT <- Data[which(Data$Geno == "WT"),]
DataHet <- Data[which(Data$Geno == "Het"),]
DataKO <- Data[which(Data$Geno == "KO"),]
#Make Age data subsets
DataP5 <- Data[which(Data$Age == "5"),]
DataP6 <- Data[which(Data$Age == "6"),]
DataP7 <- Data[which(Data$Age == "7"),]
DataP8 <- Data[which(Data$Age == "8"),]
DataP9 <- Data[which(Data$Age == "9"),]

2.2.1 Normalized Weight Across Age

#Boxplot Parameters for Norm Weight
xaxis <- "Age (arbitrary units)"
yaxis <- "Normalized Weight"
subtitle <- "All Litters"
ylim <- c(0,1.25)
#Boxplot of norm weight across age, divided by genotype
title <- "Normalized Weight by Genotype"
plotA <- bp(Data, x=Data$AgeFactor, y=Data$NormWT, fill=Data$Geno, 
                   xaxis, yaxis, ylim, title, subtitle, color_name = "Genotype", 
                   colors = geno_colors, legend_lab = geno_lab, legend_pos = bottom_right)
#Boxplot of norm weight across age, divided by sex
title <- "Normalized Weight by Sex"
plotB <- bp(Data, x=Data$AgeFactor, y=Data$NormWT, fill=Data$Sex, 
                   xaxis, yaxis="", ylim, title, subtitle, color_name = "Sex", 
                   colors = sex_colors, legend_lab = sex_lab, legend_pos = bottom_right)
#Boxplot of norm weight across age, divided by litter size
title <- "Normalized Weight by Litter Size"
plotC <- brewer_bp(Data, x=Data$AgeFactor, y=Data$NormWT, fill=Data$LitterSize, 
                   xaxis, yaxis, ylim, title, subtitle, color_name = "Litter Size", 
                   legend_lab = LS_lab, legend_pos = "right")
#Arrange boxplots into 3 panels
suppressWarnings(ggarrange(plotA, plotB, labels = c("A.","B."), ncol = 2, nrow = 1))

suppressWarnings(ggarrange(plotC, labels = c("C."), ncol = 1, nrow = 1))

Observations

Genotype
There is a significant effect of genotype on normalized weight. Post-hoc analysis are needed to determine which genotypes are different (see below).

Sex
There is a significant effect of sex on normalized weight. Males are significantly larger than females.

Litter Size
There is a strong effect of litter size, particularly at the youngest ages. This is an artefact of normalization to age 9. As seen in the raw weight data, mice from smaller litters are significantly larger at age 9 than those from larger litters However, the birth weights between mice from litters of different size are more similar than the age 9 weights. Thus, the proportion of age 9 weight at age 1 for a mouse from a small litter is smaller than the same proportion for a mouse from a larger litter. Normalizing to the heterozygous animals at each age will eliminate this artefact. Because this artefact is present for all normalized measures, the “litter size across age”" plots will be omitted for the following metrics.

Statistical Analyses
Three Way Mixed Model ANOVA
Response Variable: Normalized Weight
Between Subjects Factors: Genotype, Sex
Within Subjects Factors: Age

#Statistical analysis of normalized weight across age by genotype
model <- aov(Data$NormWT ~Data$Geno*Data$Sex*Data$Age +
                    Error(Data$PupID/Data$Age)+Data$Geno*Data$Sex, data=Data)
summary(model)

Post-Hoc: Tukey’s Honestly Significant Difference - Genotype and Age

#Posthoc TukeyHSD - Genotype at P6 - P9
mod <- TukeyHSD(aov(DataP5$NormWT ~DataP5$Geno, data = DataP5), ordered = TRUE)
P5geno <- mod$`DataP5$Geno`
mod <- TukeyHSD(aov(DataP6$NormWT ~DataP6$Geno, data = DataP6), ordered = TRUE)
P6geno <- mod$`DataP6$Geno`
mod <- TukeyHSD(aov(DataP7$NormWT ~DataP7$Geno, data = DataP7), ordered = TRUE)
P7geno <- mod$`DataP7$Geno`
mod <- TukeyHSD(aov(DataP8$NormWT ~DataP8$Geno, data = DataP8), ordered = TRUE)
P8geno <- mod$`DataP8$Geno`
mod <- TukeyHSD(aov(DataP9$NormWT ~DataP9$Geno, data = DataP9), ordered = TRUE)
P9geno <- mod$`DataP9$Geno`
Het_KO <- c(A5 = P5geno[2,4], A6 = P6geno[2,4], A7 = P7geno[2,4], A8 = P8geno[2,4], A9 =P9geno[2,4])
WT_KO <- c(A5 = P5geno[3,4], A6 = P6geno[3,4], A7 = P7geno[3,4], A8 = P8geno[3,4],A9 =P9geno[3,4])
WT_Het <- c(A5 = P5geno[1,4], A6 = P6geno[1,4], A7 = P7geno[1,4], A8 = P8geno[1,4],A9 =P9geno[1,4])
multicomp <- data.frame(WT_KO,WT_Het,Het_KO)
plotA <- bp(Data, x=Data$AgeFactor, y=Data$NormWT, fill=Data$Geno, 
                   xaxis, yaxis, ylim, title = "Normalized Weight Gain by Genotype Across Age", subtitle, color_name = "Genotype", 
                   colors = geno_colors, legend_lab = geno_lab, legend_pos = c(0.1,0.8))
tableB <- ggtexttable(format(round(multicomp,3), nsmall = 3),
            cols = c("WT vs KO", "WT vs Het", "Het vs KO"),
            theme = ttheme("blank", base_size = 10))
plotA + annotation_custom(ggplotGrob(tableB), xmax = 15, ymax = 0.6)

Post-hoc analyses reveal that mutant mice (KO, dark blue) are significantly heavier than wildtype (WT, grey, age 7 to 9) and heterozygous mice (Het, light blue, age 5 to 9). There is no significant difference in weight between heterozygous mice and wildtype at any age.

#Posthoc TukeyHSD - Sex for each genotype
mod <- TukeyHSD(aov(DataF$NormWTGain ~ DataF$Geno, data = DataF), ordered = TRUE)
Fgeno <- mod$`DataF$Geno`
mod <- TukeyHSD(aov(DataM$NormWTGain ~ DataM$Geno, data = DataM), ordered = TRUE)

            cols = c("WT vs KO", "WT vs Het", "Het vs KO"),
            theme = ttheme("blank", base_size = 10))
#Posthoc TukeyHSD - Genotype for each sex
mod <- TukeyHSD(aov(DataWT$NormWTGain ~ DataWT$Sex, data = DataWT), ordered = TRUE)
WTgeno <- mod$`DataWT$Sex`
mod <- TukeyHSD(aov(DataHet$NormWTGain ~ DataHet$Sex, data = DataHet), ordered = TRUE)
Hetgeno <- mod$`DataHet$Sex`
mod <- TukeyHSD(aov(DataKO$NormWTGain ~ DataKO$Sex, data = DataKO), ordered = TRUE)
KOgeno <- mod$`DataKO$Sex`
M_F <- c(WT = WTgeno[1,4], Het = Hetgeno[1,4], KO = KOgeno[1,4])
multicomp <- t(format(round(data.frame(M_F),3), nsmall = 3))
multicomp <- rbind(multicomp, c(WT = "", Het = "", KO = ""))
xaxis <- "Genotype"
title <- "Normalized Weight Gain by Sex"
plotC <- bp(Data, x=Data$Geno, y=Data$NormWTGain, fill=Data$Sex, 
                   xaxis, yaxis, ylim, title, subtitle, color_name = "Sex", 
                   colors = sex_colors, legend_lab = sex_lab, legend_pos = c(0.15,0.2))

            cols = c("WT", "Het", "KO"),
            rows = c("M vs F",""),
            theme = ttheme("blank", base_size = 10))
suppressWarnings(ggarrange(plotA, plotC, tableB, tableD, labels = c("A.","B."), 
                           ncol = 2, nrow = 2, heights = c(4,1)))

Normalized Weight Gain - Effect of Genotype by Sex
For female mice, wildtype (WT, grey) and heterozygous (Het, light blue) mice gain significantly less weight than mutant mice (KO, dark blue; p < 0.0001). Female wildtype and heterozygous mice and not different from one another.

For male mice, wildtype (WT, grey) mice gain significantly less weight than either heterozygous (Het) or mutant (KO) mice (p < 0.0001). Male heterozygous and mutant mice are not different from one another.

Normalized Weight Gain - Effect of Sex by Genotype
For wildtype and mutant mice, females gain significantly more weight than males (p < 0.05).
For heterozygous mice, males gain significantly more weight than females (p < 0.0001).

                           ncol = 2, nrow = 2, heights = c(4,1)))

Normalized Length Gain - Effect of Genotype by Sex
For female mice, wildtype (WT, grey) and heterozygous (Het, light blue) mice gain significantly less length than mutant mice (KO, dark blue; p < 0.0001). Female wildtype and heterozygous mice and not different from one another (p = 0.094), however, there is a trend for heterozygous female mice to gain the least length.

For male mice, wildtype (WT, grey) mice gain significantly less length than either heterozygous (Het) or mutant (KO) mice (p < 0.0001). Male heterozygous and mutant mice are not different from one another.

Normalized Length Gain - Effect of Sex by Genotype
For wildtype and mutant mice, females gain significantly more length than males (p < 0.05).
For heterozygous mice, males gain significantly more length than females (p < 0.0001).

2.3 Data Normalized to Average Heterozygous Mice Within Litter At Each Age

The purpose of this normalization is to attempt to eliminate the effect of litter size (particularly at younger ages) on the measurements, thereby allowing pooling of the data across litter size without some of the confounding effects of litter size.

However, as the reader will see, this method of normalization made the data much less interpretable, and eliminated the clear differences between genotypes seen with normalization to the average heterozygous measures at age 9 within each litter.

#Normalization:
Data$AgeNum <- as.numeric(Data$Age)
#Creating a normalized data set, wherein all data has been normalized to the average Het weight at each age within litter
#Normalized Weight
for(i in 1:length(levels(Data$Litter))){
  for(j in 1:length(levels(Data$Age))){
    Data[which(Data$Litter == levels(Data$Litter)[i]),"NormAtAgeWT"]<- 
      Data[which(Data$Litter == levels(Data$Litter)[i] & Data$AgeNum == j),"Weight"]/
      mean(Data[which(Data$Geno == "Het" & Data$AgeNum == j & Data$Litter == levels(Data$Litter)[i]),"Weight"])
  }
}
#Normalized Weight Gain
for(i in 1:length(levels(Data$Litter))){
  for(j in 1:length(levels(Data$Age))){
    Data[which(Data$Litter == levels(Data$Litter)[i]),"NormAtAgeWTGain"]<- 
      Data[which(Data$Litter == levels(Data$Litter)[i] & Data$AgeNum == j),"WTGain"]/
      mean(Data[which(Data$Geno == "Het" & Data$AgeNum == j & Data$Litter == levels(Data$Litter)[i]),"WTGain"])
  }
}
#Normalized Length
for(i in 1:length(levels(Data$Litter))){
  for(j in 1:length(levels(Data$Age))){
    Data[which(Data$Litter == levels(Data$Litter)[i]),"NormAtAgeLN"]<- 
      Data[which(Data$Litter == levels(Data$Litter)[i] & Data$AgeNum == j),"Length"]/
      mean(Data[which(Data$Geno == "Het" & Data$AgeNum == j & Data$Litter == levels(Data$Litter)[i]),"Length"])
  }
}
#Normalized Length Gain
for(i in 1:length(levels(Data$Litter))){
  for(j in 1:length(levels(Data$Age))){
    Data[which(Data$Litter == levels(Data$Litter)[i]),"NormAtAgeLNGain"]<- 
      Data[which(Data$Litter == levels(Data$Litter)[i] & Data$AgeNum == j),"LNGain"]/
      mean(Data[which(Data$Geno == "Het" & Data$AgeNum == j & Data$Litter == levels(Data$Litter)[i]),"LNGain"])
  }
}
#Normalized BMI
for(i in 1:length(levels(Data$Litter))){
  for(j in 1:length(levels(Data$Age))){
    Data[which(Data$Litter == levels(Data$Litter)[i]),"NormAtAgeBMI"]<- 
      Data[which(Data$Litter == levels(Data$Litter)[i] & Data$AgeNum == j),"BMI"]/
      mean(Data[which(Data$Geno == "Het" & Data$AgeNum == j & Data$Litter == levels(Data$Litter)[i]),"BMI"])
  }
}
#Creating subsets by sex
DataF <- Data[which(Data$Sex == "F"),]
DataM <- Data[which(Data$Sex == "M"),]
#Creating subsets by genotype
DataWT <- Data[which(Data$Geno == "WT"),]
DataHet <- Data[which(Data$Geno == "Het"),]
DataKO <- Data[which(Data$Geno == "KO"),]
#Make Age data subsets
DataP6 <- Data[which(Data$Age == "10"),]
DataP7 <- Data[which(Data$Age == "12"),]
DataP8 <- Data[which(Data$Age == "14"),]
DataP9 <- Data[which(Data$Age == "9"),]

Observations

Genotype and Sex
When data are normalized to the average weight of heterozygous mice at each age, within each litter, there are no effects of genotype or sex on normalized weight.

Litter Size
Normalizing the data to the average heterozygous weights within litter at each age has reduced the effect of litter size overall. There are a few ages at which the litter size is a significant factor, however, this is likely driven by outlier litters.

#Posthoc TukeyHSD - Sex for each genotype

                   xaxis, yaxis, ylim, title, subtitle, color_name = "Genotype", 
                   colors = geno_colors, legend_lab = geno_lab, legend_pos = c(0.15,0.2))
tableB <- ggtexttable(format(round(multicomp,3), nsmall = 3),
            cols = c("WT vs KO", "WT vs Het", "Het vs KO"),
            theme = ttheme("blank", base_size = 10))
#Posthoc TukeyHSD - Genotype for each sex
mod <- TukeyHSD(aov(DataWT$NormAtAgeLNGain ~ DataWT$Sex, data = DataWT), ordered = TRUE)
WTgeno <- mod$`DataWT$Sex`
mod <- TukeyHSD(aov(DataHet$NormAtAgeLNGain ~ DataHet$Sex, data = DataHet), ordered = TRUE)
Hetgeno <- mod$`DataHet$Sex`
mod <- TukeyHSD(aov(DataKO$NormAtAgeLNGain ~ DataKO$Sex, data = DataKO), ordered = TRUE)
KOgeno <- mod$`DataKO$Sex`
M_F <- c(WT = WTgeno[1,4], Het = Hetgeno[1,4], KO = KOgeno[1,4])
multicomp <- t(format(round(data.frame(M_F),3), nsmall = 3))
multicomp <- rbind(multicomp, c(WT = "", Het = "", KO = ""))
xaxis <- "Genotype"
title <- "Normalized Length Gain by Sex"
plotC <- bp(Data, x=Data$Geno, y=Data$NormAtAgeLNGain, fill=Data$Sex, 
                   xaxis, yaxis, ylim, title, subtitle, color_name = "Sex", 
                   colors = sex_colors, legend_lab = sex_lab, legend_pos = c(0.15,0.2))
tableD <- ggtexttable(multicomp,
            cols = c("WT", "Het", "KO"),
            rows = c("M vs F",""),
            theme = ttheme("blank", base_size = 10))
suppressWarnings(ggarrange(plotA, plotC, tableB, tableD, labels = c("A.","B."), 
                           ncol = 2, nrow = 2, heights = c(4,1)))

Normalized Length Gain - Effect of Genotype by Sex
For female mice, there is a trend for mutant mice (KO, dark blue) to have higher normalized length gain (at age) compared to heterozygous mice (Het, light blue; p = 0.053). There are no differences between genotypes for male mice.

Normalized Length Gain - Effect of Sex by Genotype
For wildtype mice (WT), female mice gain significantly more length than male mice (p = 0.041), when the data is normalized to heterozygous mice at each age, within each litter.

2.3.7 Discussion

This method of normalization of measures to average heterozygous mice within each litter at each age appears to abolish the effects of genotype which are seen clearly in the data that were normalized to average measures at age 9 of heterozygous mice within each litter. Therefore, that analysis is most useful and interpretable, and should be used instead of this one.

Observations

Genotype
There is a significant effect of genotype on normalized weight. Post-hoc analysis are needed to determine which genotypes are different (see below).

Sex

Litter Size
As expected, there is an effect of litter size at the earliest ages (artefact of normalization to average hets at age 9).

Statistical Analyses
Three Way Mixed Model ANOVA
Response Variable: Normalized Weight
Between Subjects Factors: Genotype, Sex
Within Subjects Factors: Age

#Statistical analysis of normalized weight across age by genotype
model <- aov(DataLS2to5$NormWT ~DataLS2to5$Geno*DataLS2to5$Sex*DataLS2to5$Age +
                    Error(DataLS2to5$PupID/DataLS2to5$Age)+DataLS2to5$Geno*DataLS2to5$Sex, data=DataLS2to5)

Post-hoc analyses reveal that mutant mice (KO, dark blue) are significantly heavier than wildtype (WT, grey, age 8 - 9, p < 0.005) and heterozygous mice (Het, light blue, age 5 - 9, p < 0.016). There is no significant difference in normalized weight between heterozygous and wildtype mice at any age.

Post-hoc analysis reveals that, for normalized BMI, heterozygous mice (Het, light blue) had significantly lower normalized BMI at the earliest ages (2 - 3, p-value not shown in table). However, there were no significant differences in normalized BMI between genotypes at the older ages. The differences at younger ages may be due to an artefact of normalization to average heterozygous mice at age 9 within each litter.

Overall, normalized BMI is not different between genotypes, indicating that the differences in weight and length seen between genotypes are proportional, resulting in similar BMI.

Observations
There is a strong effect of genotype and sex for both normalized weight gain and normalized length gain, but not normalized BMI.

2.4.5 Statistical Analysis of Normalized Weight Gain

Two Way ANOVA
Response Variable: Normalized Weight Gain
Between Subjects Factors: Genotype, Sex

#Statistical analysis of normalized weight gain by genotype and sex
model <- aov(DataLS2to5$NormWTGain ~DataLS2to5$Geno*DataLS2to5$Sex, data=DataLS2to5)
summary(model)
                                Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value   Pr(>F)    
DataLS2to5$Geno                  2 0.8587  0.4293   91.92  < 2e-16 ***
DataLS2to5$Sex                   1 0.2416  0.2416   51.72 1.74e-12 ***
DataLS2to5$Geno:DataLS2to5$Sex   2 0.1935  0.0967   20.71 1.89e-09 ***
Residuals                      660 3.0827  0.0047                     
---
Signif. codes:  0 *** 0.001 ** 0.01 * 0.05 . 0.1   1

There is a significant interaction between genotype and sex (p < 0.0001).

Post-Hoc: Tukey’s Honestly Significant Difference - Genotype and Sex

#Posthoc TukeyHSD - Sex for each genotype
mod <- TukeyHSD(aov(DataLS2to5F$NormWTGain ~ DataLS2to5F$Geno, data = DataLS2to5F), ordered = TRUE)
Fgeno <- mod$`DataLS2to5F$Geno`
mod <- TukeyHSD(aov(DataLS2to5M$NormWTGain ~ DataLS2to5M$Geno, data = DataLS2to5M), ordered = TRUE)
Mgeno <- mod$`DataLS2to5M$Geno`
Het_KO <- c(Female = Fgeno[2,4], Male = Mgeno[2,4])
WT_KO <- c(Female = Fgeno[3,4], Male = Mgeno[3,4])
WT_Het <- c(Female = Fgeno[1,4], Male = Mgeno[1,4])
multicomp <- data.frame(WT_KO,WT_Het,Het_KO)
xaxis <- "Sex"
yaxis <- "Normalized Weight Gain"
ylim <- c(0.6,1.2)
title <- "Normalized Weight Gain by Genotype"
plotA <- bp(DataLS2to5, x=DataLS2to5$Sex, y=DataLS2to5$NormWTGain, fill=DataLS2to5$Geno, 
                   xaxis, yaxis, ylim, title, subtitle, color_name = "Genotype", 
                   colors = geno_colors, legend_lab = geno_lab, legend_pos = c(0.15,0.2))
tableB <- ggtexttable(format(round(multicomp,3), nsmall = 3),
            cols = c("WT vs KO", "WT vs Het", "Het vs KO"),
            theme = ttheme("blank", base_size = 10))
#Posthoc TukeyHSD - Genotype for each sex
mod <- TukeyHSD(aov(DataLS2to5WT$NormWTGain ~ DataLS2to5WT$Sex, data = DataLS2to5WT), ordered = TRUE)
WTgeno <- mod$`DataLS2to5WT$Sex`
mod <- TukeyHSD(aov(DataLS2to5Het$NormWTGain ~ DataLS2to5Het$Sex, data = DataLS2to5Het), ordered = TRUE)
Hetgeno <- mod$`DataLS2to5Het$Sex`
mod <- TukeyHSD(aov(DataLS2to5KO$NormWTGain ~ DataLS2to5KO$Sex, data = DataLS2to5KO), ordered = TRUE)
KOgeno <- mod$`DataLS2to5KO$Sex`
M_F <- c(WT = WTgeno[1,4], Het = Hetgeno[1,4], KO = KOgeno[1,4])
multicomp <- t(format(round(data.frame(M_F),3), nsmall = 3))
multicomp <- rbind(multicomp, c(WT = "", Het = "", KO = ""))
xaxis <- "Genotype"
title <- "Normalized Weight Gain by Sex"
plotC <- bp(DataLS2to5, x=DataLS2to5$Geno, y=DataLS2to5$NormWTGain, fill=DataLS2to5$Sex, 
                   xaxis, yaxis, ylim, title, subtitle, color_name = "Sex", 
                   colors = sex_colors, legend_lab = sex_lab, legend_pos = c(0.15,0.2))
tableD <- ggtexttable(multicomp,
            cols = c("WT", "Het", "KO"),
            rows = c("M vs F",""),
            theme = ttheme("blank", base_size = 10))
suppressWarnings(ggarrange(plotA, plotC, tableB, tableD, labels = c("A.","B."), 
                           ncol = 2, nrow = 2, heights = c(4,1)))

Normalized Weight Gain - Effect of Genotype by Sex
For female mice, mutant mice (KO, dark blue) gain significantly more weight than either heterozygous (Het, light blue, p < 0.0001) or wildtype mice (WT, grey, p < 0.0001), which are not different from one another.

For male mice, both mutant (KO, dark blue) and heterozygous (Het, light blue) mice gain significantly more weight than wildtype mice (WT, grey, p < 0.0001). Mutant and heterozygous male mice are not significantly different, although there is a trend towards mutant mice gaining more weight than heterozygous mice (p = 0.058).

Normalized Weight Gain - Effect of Sex by Genotype
For wildtype and mutant mice, there is not effect of sex on normalized weight gain. For heterozygous mice, males gain significantly more weight than females.

                           ncol = 2, nrow = 2, heights = c(4,1)))

Normalized Length Gain - Effect of Genotype by Sex
For female mice, mutant mice (KO, dark blue) gain significantly more length than either heterozygous (Het, light blue, p < 0.0001) or wildtype mice (WT, grey, p < 0.0001), which are not different from one another.

For male mice, heterozygous (Het, light blue) mice gained significantly more length than either wildtype (WT, grey, p < 0.0001) or mutant (KO, dark blue, p < 0.0001) mice. There was a trend towards mutant mice gaining significantly more length than wildtype mice (p = 0.053), however, this difference likely failed to reach significance due to mutant outliers.

Normalized Length Gain - Effect of Sex by Genotype
For wildtype and mutant mice, female mice gained significantly more length than male mice. For heterozygous mice, males gain significantly more length than females.

Two Way ANOVA
Response Variable: Normalized BMI at age 9
Between Subjects Factors: Genotype, Sex

#Statistical analysis of normalized BMI atage 9 genotype

DataLS2to5P9$Sex                    1 0.00810 0.008100   3.495 0.0659 .

Residuals                          68 0.15762 0.002318

52 observations deleted due to missingness

There was a significant effect of genotype on normalized BMI at Age 9.

Post-Hoc: Tukey’s Honestly Significant Difference - Genotype

DataLS2to5P9 <- DataLS2to5P9[complete.cases(DataLS2to5P9$NormBMI),]
#Posthoc TukeyHSD 
mod <- TukeyHSD(aov(DataLS2to5P9$NormBMI ~ DataLS2to5P9$Geno, data = DataLS2to5P9), ordered = TRUE)
Geno <- mod$`DataLS2to5P9$Geno`
Het_KO <- Geno[2,4]
WT_KO <- Geno[3,4]
WT_Het <- Geno[1,4]
multicomp <- data.frame(WT_KO,WT_Het,Het_KO)
xaxis <- "Genotype"
yaxis <- "Normalized BMI at Age 9"
ylim <- c(0.6,1.2)
title <- "Normalized BMI at Age 9 by Genotype"
plotA <- bp(DataLS2to5P9, x=DataLS2to5P9$Geno, y=DataLS2to5P9$NormBMI, fill=DataLS2to5P9$Geno, 
                   xaxis, yaxis, ylim, title, subtitle, color_name = "Genotype", 
                   colors = geno_colors, legend_lab = geno_lab, legend_pos = c(0.1,0.2))
tableB <- ggtexttable(format(round(multicomp,3), nsmall = 3),
            cols = c("WT vs KO", "WT vs Het", "Het vs KO"),
            rows = c(""),
            theme = ttheme("blank", base_size = 10))
ggarrange(plotA, tableB, labels = c("A.","B."), ncol = 1, nrow = 2, heights = c(4,1))

Posthoc analyses reveal that mutant mice (KO, dark blue) have significantly greater normalized BMI at age 9 as compared to wildtype mice (WT, grey, p = 0.048). There is no significant difference in normalized BMI at age 9 between heterozygous mice (Het, light blue) and wildtype mice (p = 0.973). There is a trend towards mutant mice having greater normalized BMI at age 9 as compared to heterozygous mice (p = 0.088).
